# Group off-peak prices by companies and month
monthly_price_by_id = price_df.groupby(['id', 'price_date']).agg({'price_off_peak_var': 'mean', 'price_off_peak_fix': 'mean'}).reset_index()

# Get january and december prices
jan_prices = monthly_price_by_id.groupby('id').first().reset_index()
dec_prices = monthly_price_by_id.groupby('id').last().reset_index() 

# Calculate the difference
diff = pd.merge(dec_prices.rename(columns={'price_off_peak_var': 'dec_1', 'price_off_peak_fix': 'dec_2'}), jan_prices.drop(columns='price_date'), on='id')
diff['offpeak_diff_dec_jan_energy'] = diff['dec_1'] - diff['price_off_peak_var']
diff['offpeak_diff_dec_jan_power'] = diff['dec_2'] - diff['price_off_peak_fix']
diff = diff[['id', 'offpeak_diff_dec_jan_energy','offpeak_diff_dec_jan_power']]

Let us create some more features that can be created from price data

Like our collegue created a feature i.e., difference between the off peak prices in dec & jan of preceeding year, we can also create following features for both energy & power :

  • avg price difference across time period
  • max price difference across time period & month

3.2 Avg price difference across time period

This feature will give some granuality to the yearly difference feature. This feature can play important role as it can reveal pattern on granual scale.

Lets move to other columns in clients data

3.4 Convert dates into months

As the predective models works better with numerical or categorical data & cant work with dates, so lets convert dates columns into number of months

We have 4 datetime features:

  • date_activ = date of activation of the contract
  • date_end = registered date of the end of the contract
  • date_modif_prod = date of the last modification of the product
  • date_renewal = date of the next contract renewal

From these features, we can create new features as follows:

  • (refernce date = Jan 2016)
  • active_period = # of months active
  • expiry_period = # of months of the contract left
  • modif_prod_period = # of months since last modification
  • renewal_period = # of months since last renewal

How these features can be helpful to determin the churn:

  • the clients who have higher active_period months will be more loyal as compared to the clients with lower no.of months
  • the less number of months left in the contract can signal that client will be looking for better deals in market, if there are a lot of months left, so it could be possible that they can break the contract if not satified. if there are in middle of contarct period, some charges might be applied so the clients dont leave in between.
  • if the modification has been done, that means they are custimizing the services as per clients needs that means client is less likely to churn.
  • if the months since last renewal is less that means the clients is staying & if the number is more then there is decision time for client to look for better deals in market.
In [16]:
# Lets calculate these columns

df['Current date'] = '1-01-2016'
df['Current date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Current date'])
df['active_p'] = ((df['Current date'] - df['date_activ'])/np.timedelta64(1, 'M')).astype(int)
df['expiry_p'] =  ((df['date_end'] - df['Current date'])/np.timedelta64(1, 'M')).astype(int)
df['modif_prod_p'] =  ((df['Current date'] - df['date_modif_prod'])/np.timedelta64(1, 'M')).astype(int)
df['renewal_p'] = ((df['Current date'] - df['date_renewal'])/np.timedelta64(1, 'M')).astype(int)

3.5 Numerical Columns

Addressing the skewness of numerical features is not a strict requirement when building a random forest model. Random forests are generally robust to outliers and skewed data, which is one of their strengths. However, addressing skewness in numerical features can sometimes improve the performance of the model.

Logarithmic transformation (log): This transformation is useful for reducing right-skewness and compressing large values. It is often used when dealing with data that has exponential growth or multiplicative relationships.

def plot_heatmap(correlation_matrix):
    # Plot correlation
    plt.figure(figsize=(45, 45))
    sns.heatmap(
    correlation_matrix,
    xticklabels=correlation_matrix.columns.values,
    yticklabels=correlation_matrix.columns.values,
    annot=True,
    annot_kws={'size': 12}
    )
    # Axis ticks size
    plt.xticks(fontsize=15)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=15)
    plt.show()

In [31]:
# Set the threshold for high correlation
correlation_threshold = 0.85

correlation_dict = {}

correlation_matrix =df.corr()

# Find pairs of highly correlated features and populate the dictionary
for i in range(len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
    correlated_features = set()
    for j in range(i + 1, len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
        if abs(correlation_matrix.iloc[i, j]) > correlation_threshold:
            correlated_features.add(correlation_matrix.columns[j])
    if correlated_features:
        correlation_dict[correlation_matrix.columns[i]] = correlated_features

Feature Engineering is a recursive process by trail & error. Once we train our model & get the predictions, we will be abe to see the feature impoprtnce in case of Random Forest Model. Lets pause the feature engineering as of now & proceed.

Random Forest often outperforms other classification models due to the following reasons:

1) Reduced Overfitting: Random feature selection and data sampling during tree building reduce overfitting, making it less sensitive to noisy data.

2) Ensemble of Diverse Trees: It combines multiple decision trees, each trained on different subsets of data and features, leading to a more accurate and robust model.

3) Robust to Outliers: Outliers have less impact as decisions are made based on majority votes, making it resilient to noisy data points.

4) Captures Non-linearity: Random Forest can model complex non-linear relationships in data, effectively handling intricate patterns.

5) Handles High-Dimensional Data: It performs well with datasets containing a large number of features without requiring extensive feature engineering.

6) Feature Importance: It naturally computes feature importance, aiding in feature selection and interpretation of results.

7) Less Prone to Bias: Unlike some models, Random Forest is less susceptible to bias as individual trees can balance each other's biases.

8) Limited Hyperparameter Tuning: Requires fewer hyperparameters to tune compared to other complex models, simplifying the optimization process.

9) Generalization: Random Forest performs well on both unseen data and training data, striking a balance between bias and variance.

10) Handling Missing Values: It can handle missing values without explicit imputation, streamlining the data preprocessing phase.

These factors collectively contribute to Random Forest's ability to provide accurate and reliable classifications across a wide range of datasets and scenarios.

What parameters to choose for training the Random Forest Model

  • Setting "n_jobs" to -1 in the RandomForestClassifier hyperparameters indicates that you want to utilize all available CPU cores for parallel processing when building the individual decision trees in the forest. This can significantly speed up the training process, especially for larger datasets and models with a higher number of estimators (trees).

  • Setting "random_state" to a specific value, such as random_state = 42, ensures that your results are reproducible, which is important for consistent testing, debugging, and comparing different experiments.

  • Setting "class_weight" to 'balanced' automatically adjusts the weights inversely proportional to class frequencies. This is important when dealing with imbalanced datasets to ensure that the model pays appropriate attention to minority classes.

What parameters to choose for hyperparameter tuning

  • n_estimators: This hyperparameter controls the number of decision trees in the forest. Increasing the number of trees can lead to a more robust and accurate model, but it also increases computation time. It's important to find a balance between model performance and computational efficiency.

  • max_depth: This hyperparameter restricts the maximum depth of each decision tree in the forest. A shallow tree (low max_depth) might be underfitting and not capture complex patterns, while a deep tree (high max_depth) can lead to overfitting. It's essential to tune this parameter to prevent overfitting and find the optimal level of tree depth.

  • min_samples_split: This hyperparameter defines the minimum number of samples required to split an internal node. A higher value reduces the tree's tendency to overfit by preventing further splitting when there are only a few samples left in a node. Adjusting this parameter can help control the balance between model complexity and generalization.

How to address the class imbalance problem while training & cross validation

"StratifiedKFold" is a cross-validation technique used to address the potential issue of class imbalance in the training and validation splits during the evaluation of machine learning models. It's particularly useful when you have imbalanced datasets, where one class has significantly fewer samples than the other(s).

The traditional KFold cross-validation technique splits the dataset into k folds, where each fold is used as a validation set once and the rest as the training set. However, if your data is imbalanced, there's a risk that some folds may not contain representative samples of the minority class, leading to poor generalization.

StratifiedKFold addresses this by ensuring that each fold maintains the same class distribution as the original dataset. In other words, each fold will have a similar proportion of each class as the full dataset. This helps in improving the reliability of the cross-validation process, especially for imbalanced datasets.

Choice of Evaluation Metrics

In churn prediction, recall is crucial as it minimizes missed opportunities by focusing on identifying actual churn cases, which helps businesses retain customers and mitigate revenue loss due to false negatives.

Precision is vital in churn prediction as it ensures accurate identification of customers likely to leave, minimizing costly false positive predictions, optimizing resource allocation, and preserving customer trust by avoiding unnecessary retention efforts. It contributes to efficient decision-making and resource management while minimizing customer dissatisfaction.

To obtain the best results for two evaluation metrics, such as "Recall" and "Precision," you can use the refit parameter of the GridSearchCV to specify the primary metric you want to optimize.

In [47]:
# Define a parameter grid for hyperparameter tuning
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators' : [200, 300, 400, 500],
    'max_depth': [10, 12, 15, 20, 30, 35],
    'min_samples_split': [5, 8, 10]
}

# Create StratifiedKFold 
stratified_cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

# Create a Random Forest model
random_forest_model = RandomForestClassifier(
    random_state=42,
    class_weight='balanced',
    n_jobs=-1
)

# Define custom scoring that includes both precision and recall
scoring = {
    'recall': make_scorer(recall_score),
    'precision': make_scorer(precision_score)
}

# Use GridSearchCV for hyperparameter tuning
grid_search = GridSearchCV(random_forest_model, param_grid, cv=stratified_cv, scoring=scoring, refit='recall')
grid_search.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)

# Get the best parameters from the grid search
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print("Best Hyperparameters:")
print(best_params)

best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
print("Best Model:")
print(best_model)

# Fit the model on the training data with the best parameters
best_random_forest_model = best_model

# Fit the model on the resampled training data
best_random_forest_model.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)

# Make predictions on the test data
predictions = best_random_forest_model.predict(X_test)

Conclusion

Precision-Recall Balance: The model achieved a total of 249 true positives, indicating its ability to correctly identify actual churn cases. However, the number of false positives (1124) raises concerns about the precision of the positive predictions.

Negative Predictions: The model performed well in identifying true negatives (2832) which indicates its proficiency in recognizing cases where customers are likely to retain their services.

Missed Churn Cases: The model also had 177 false negatives, implying instances where actual churn cases were not accurately predicted. This suggests a need to improve the model's recall to capture more churn cases.

Business Impact: The high number of false positives might lead to unnecessary retention efforts, potentially straining resources and customer relationships. Addressing this is crucial to ensure efficient resource allocation.

Balancing Act: Balancing precision and recall is pivotal in this context. Adjusting the classification threshold can help strike a balance between minimizing false positives and capturing more true positives.

Refinement Opportunities: The model's performance can be enhanced through techniques such as adjusting class weights, feature engineering, and parameter tuning to improve precision and recall simultaneously.

Domain Expertise: Collaborating with domain experts to better understand exiting factors as well as other features influencing churn and refining features could lead to a more accurate model.
